{"text": "A; (123)\n\nwhereIL(IR) is the current entering the left (right) normal lead from the scattering region,\n\nandVL(VR). In the limit of a long wire, GLLandGRRare the local conductances at each\n\nend that we discussed in the last sub-section and are plotted in the left panel of Fig. 5. The\n\ntransport properties across the wire would be measured from the nonlocal conductances ( GLR\n\nandGRL). These non-nonlocal conductances can be written in terms of the transmission\n\nprobabilities de\n\nned in Eq. 112\n\nGij=e2\n\nh(Tee\n\nij\u0000Teh\n\nij); i6=j; (124)\n\nand are therefore expecteed to vanish for a gapped wire (away from the topological phase\n\ntransition).\n\nThe appearance of a\n\nnite non-local conductance near zero bias would signal such a bulk\n\ngap closure. This expectation is veri\n\ned115is veri\n\ned by the numerical results for the non-\n\nlocal conductance shown in the middle panels Fig. 3. These results were obtained for a\n\nscattering matrix Scomputed using KWANT100using the BdG Hamiltonian Eq. 74 for a\n\nnanowire. An unfortunate complication of these results is that the non-local conductance\n\nactually, even at the topological phase transition, vanishes at exactly zero bias as a conse-\n\nquence of particle-hole symmetry116. While the vanishing at the critical point is linear in\n\nvoltage as shown in the right panel of Fig. 3 as opposed to a gapped signal away from the\n\nphase transition, introduction of disorder etc might make the bulk gap closure di\u000ecult to\n\nidentify in a de\n\nnitive way. It is worth mentioning that an advantge of the scattering matrix\n\nformalism is that we do not need the bulk Hamiltonian or the topological condition Eq. 94,\n\nwhich are limited to clean single-band systems, to identify the topology of the nanowire.", "embedding": [0.009213226, 0.00917933, 0.0026779987, 0.026433991, 0.016580312, -0.017974997, 0.037434887, -0.038822014, -0.043641344, 0.104241066, 0.05558589, -0.012570335, -0.012358244